1️⃣ What do you mean by Structures?
Explanation:

A structure in C is a user-defined data type that allows you to combine variables of different data types into a single unit.

It is used to represent a record — for example, a student record that includes name, roll number, and marks.

Example:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

struct Student {
    int roll_no;
    char name[50];
    float marks;
};

int main() {
    struct Student s1;

    s1.roll_no = 496;
    strcpy(s1.name, "Suryansh");
    s1.marks = 88.5;

    printf("Student Details:\n");
    printf("Roll No: %d\n", s1.roll_no);
    printf("Name: %s\n", s1.name);
    printf("Marks: %.2f\n", s1.marks);

    return 0;
}

Output:
Student Details:
Roll No: 496
Name: Suryansh
Marks: 88.50

2️⃣ What do you mean by Array & Pointer Array?
Array:

An array is a collection of elements of the same data type, stored in contiguous memory locations.

Example:

int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

Pointer Array:

An array of pointers is a collection where each element is a pointer (address variable).

Example:

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    char *names[3] = {"Ram", "Shyam", "Suryansh"};

    for(int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        printf("%s\n", names[i]);
    }
    return 0;
}

Output:
Ram
Shyam
Sueyansh

3️⃣ Compare Two Structure Variables (== and != operators)

In C, you cannot directly use == or != to compare structure variables.
You must compare each member manually or use memcmp() from <string.h>.

Example:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

struct Point {
    int x;
    int y;
};

int main() {
    struct Point p1 = {10, 20};
    struct Point p2 = {10, 20};

    if (p1.x == p2.x && p1.y == p2.y)
        printf("Both structures are EQUAL.\n");
    else
        printf("Structures are NOT EQUAL.\n");

    return 0;
}

Output:
Both structures are EQUAL.

4️⃣ Perform Arithmetic Operations on Structures

Although you cannot directly add or subtract structures,
you can perform arithmetic operations on their members.

Example:
#include <stdio.h>

struct Complex {
    int real;
    int imag;
};

int main() {
    struct Complex c1 = {5, 3};
    struct Complex c2 = {2, 4};
    struct Complex sum, diff;

    sum.real = c1.real + c2.real;
    sum.imag = c1.imag + c2.imag;

    diff.real = c1.real - c2.real;
    diff.imag = c1.imag - c2.imag;

    printf("First Complex Number: %d + %di\n", c1.real, c1.imag);
    printf("Second Complex Number: %d + %di\n", c2.real, c2.imag);
    printf("Sum: %d + %di\n", sum.real, sum.imag);
    printf("Difference: %d + %di\n", diff.real, diff.imag);

    return 0;
}

Output:
First Complex Number: 5 + 3i
Second Complex Number: 2 + 4i
Sum: 7 + 7i
Difference: 3 - 1i
